<subSubSection id="E5B9651DEF09DE01FF07F9B8FBC35587" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FF07F9B8FE96503F" blockId="4.[189,797,1468,1919]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FF07F9B8FEBF5138" bold="true" box="[189,366,1575,1599]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FF07F9B8FED55138" box="[189,260,1575,1599]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Adult</collectorName>
habitus.
</emphasis>
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FECFF9B8FE035138" box="[373,466,1575,1599]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">General</collectorName>
color pale yellow patterned with pale brown. 
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FE24F9D4FE0F5164" box="[414,478,1611,1635]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Head</collectorName>
pattern indistinct, almost entirely yellow with only slightly darkened lappets (
<figureCitation id="35982A13EF09DE01FF7FF90DFED651AD" box="[197,263,1682,1706]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1539,1563]" captionTargetBox="[325,1308,251,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-146@3.[325,1308,251,1452]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 6-10. Anacroneuria cushueme male structures. 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Abdominal sternum 9. 8. Aedeagus, ventral. 9. Aedeagus, lateral. 10. Aedeagus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760784/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). 
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FEA0F90DFE4051AE" box="[282,401,1682,1705]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Pronotum</collectorName>
with sublateral pale brown bands; area adjacent to median suture and anterolateral margins pale. 
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FECAF946FE1851F7" box="[368,457,1753,1776]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Femora</collectorName>
pale brown, tibiae slightly darker at apex and base. 
<collectorName id="00565340EF09DE01FE4BF963FDEC5013" box="[497,573,1788,1812]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Wings</collectorName>
transparent, veins pale amber.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FF07F8DBFC26553E" blockId="4.[189,797,1468,1919]" lastBlockId="4.[835,1444,225,1209]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FF07F8DBFED3505B" bold="true" box="[189,258,1860,1884]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Male.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity id="6A5B9B73EF09DE01FE53F8DBFDE6505C" box="[489,567,1860,1884]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
. Apical section of aedeagus with median, projecting lobe narrowed slightly from base and truncate at tip (
<figureCitation id="35982A13EF09DE01FAF2FF7EFA4457FE" box="[1352,1429,225,249]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1539,1563]" captionTargetBox="[325,1308,251,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-146@3.[325,1308,251,1452]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 6-10. Anacroneuria cushueme male structures. 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Abdominal sternum 9. 8. Aedeagus, ventral. 9. Aedeagus, lateral. 10. Aedeagus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760784/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Shoulders strongly sclerotized, bulging laterad; body of aedeagus wider proximal to shoulder bases. Dorsal keel consists of two long, divergent ridges and two pairs of shorter ones near base of longer median keel lines (
<figureCitation id="35982A13EF09DE01FB90FE0DFBAE56AD" box="[1066,1151,402,426]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1539,1563]" captionTargetBox="[325,1308,251,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-146@3.[325,1308,251,1452]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 6-10. Anacroneuria cushueme male structures. 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Abdominal sternum 9. 8. Aedeagus, ventral. 9. Aedeagus, lateral. 10. Aedeagus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760784/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Hooks relatively wide and acute. Lateral lobes on apical section project away from aedeagal body, one pair lunate and the other almost quadrate (
<figureCitation id="35982A13EF09DE01FBD6FE62FB675512" box="[1132,1206,509,533]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1539,1563]" captionTargetBox="[325,1308,251,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-146@3.[325,1308,251,1452]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 6-10. Anacroneuria cushueme male structures. 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Abdominal sternum 9. 8. Aedeagus, ventral. 9. Aedeagus, lateral. 10. Aedeagus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760784/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Hammer thimble shaped (
<figureCitation id="35982A13EF09DE01FC1DFDBFFC3B553E" box="[935,1002,544,569]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[189,241,1539,1563]" captionTargetBox="[325,1308,251,1462]" captionTargetId="figure-146@3.[325,1308,251,1452]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 6-10. Anacroneuria cushueme male structures. 6. Head and pronotum. 7. Abdominal sternum 9. 8. Aedeagus, ventral. 9. Aedeagus, lateral. 10. Aedeagus, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760784/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FCF9FDDBFBF7555B" blockId="4.[835,1444,225,1209]" box="[835,1062,580,604]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FCF9FDDBFC70555B" bold="true" box="[835,929,580,604]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FCF9FDF7FBC35587" blockId="4.[835,1444,225,1209]" box="[835,1042,616,640]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FCF9FDF7FC5F5587" bold="true" box="[835,910,616,640]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Larva.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5B9651DEF09DE01FCF9FD13FACD55C0" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FCF9FD13FACD55C0" blockId="4.[835,1444,225,1209]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FCF9FD13FC1C55A3" bold="true" box="[835,973,652,676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name, used as a noun in apposition, is based on the 
<typeStatus id="72188834EF09DE01FB39FD2FFB6655CF" box="[1155,1207,688,712]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E5B9651DEF09DE01FCF9FD4CFC2653BE" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="AD1C3696EF09DE01FCF9FD4CFC2653BE" blockId="4.[835,1444,225,1209]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FCF9FD4CFC1555EC" bold="true" box="[835,964,723,747]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Based on aedeagal morphology, this species is related to the 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FBE7FD68FA725408" authority="Stark &amp; Sivec 1998" authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="1998" box="[1117,1443,759,783]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yameo">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FBE7FD68FB135408" box="[1117,1218,759,783]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. yameo</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C9324B67EF09DE01FB73FD68FA725408" author="Stark, B. P. &amp; I. Sivec" box="[1225,1443,759,783]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref6613" refString="Stark, B. P. &amp; I. Sivec. 1998. Anacroneuria of Peru and Bolivia (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Scopolia, 40: 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="1998">Stark &amp; Sivec 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
group of species, which also includes 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FB4DFC84FC355451" authority="Stark &amp; Sivec 1998" authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="1998" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pakitza">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FB4DFC84FAB35435" box="[1271,1378,794,818]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. pakitza</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C9324B67EF09DE01FAD2FC85FC355451" author="Stark, B. P. &amp; I. Sivec" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" pagination="1 - 64" refId="ref6613" refString="Stark, B. P. &amp; I. Sivec. 1998. Anacroneuria of Peru and Bolivia (Plecoptera: Perlidae). Scopolia, 40: 1 - 64." type="journal article" year="1998">Stark &amp; Sivec 1998</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FC4EFCA1FB305451" authority="Stark 1995" authorityName="Stark" authorityYear="1995" box="[1012,1249,830,854]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pinza">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FC4EFCA1FB845451" box="[1012,1109,830,854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. pinza</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="C9324B67EF09DE01FBDBFCA1FB305451" author="Stark, B. P." box="[1121,1249,830,854]" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" pagination="211 - 249" refId="ref6406" refString="Stark, B. P. 1995. New species and records of Anacroneuria (Klapalek) from Venezuela. Spixiana, 18: 211 - 249." type="journal article" year="1995">Stark 1995</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FA90FCA1FC6F547D" authority="Stark 2001" authorityName="Stark" authorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zunigae">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FA90FCA1FA725451" box="[1322,1443,830,854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. zunigae</emphasis>
Stark 2001
</taxonomicName>
. The new species bears a greater similarity in aedeagal structure to 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FBE3FC1AFB6D549A" authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="1998" box="[1113,1212,901,925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yameo">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FBE3FC1AFB6D549A" box="[1113,1212,901,925]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. yameo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FB49FC1AFA8C549A" authorityName="Stark &amp; Sivec" authorityYear="1998" box="[1267,1373,901,925]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pakitza">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FB49FC1AFA8C549A" box="[1267,1373,901,925]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. pakitza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in these species the shoulder region bulges toward the aedeagal apex creating an apically trilobed structure; this is quite distinct in the dorsal aspect and differs from the comparable structures in 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FB68FB8CFA89532C" authorityName="Stark &amp; Gill" authorityYear="2012" box="[1234,1368,1043,1067]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cushueme">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FB68FB8CFA89532C" box="[1234,1368,1043,1067]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. cushueme</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which bulge more laterad. In 
<taxonomicName id="6AA34D15EF09DE01FBC5FBA8FAC55348" authorityName="Stark &amp; Gill" authorityYear="2012" box="[1151,1300,1079,1103]" class="Insecta" family="Perlidae" genus="Anacroneuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cushueme">
<emphasis id="9FD7EA84EF09DE01FBC5FBA8FAC55348" box="[1151,1300,1079,1103]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="82">A. cushueme</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the mesal projection of the aedeagal apex is truncate at the tip and broad at the base which also differs from both related species.
</paragraph>
